</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ughie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ghie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 494<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/16/02 6:33:38 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3470.topic&index=18>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Social Security</span><hr size=1> I am a democrat.<br>
<br>
I think Bush is doing a good job, except where Israel is concerned. But thats nothing to do with this. <br>
<br>
I think blaming the current politics for the economy at the moment is ludicris.<br>
<br>
9/11 shook the american confidence pretty hard.<br>
<br>
Only on very few occasions have politics had any directly noticiable effect on the american economy. For the most part the economy is an independant entity with its own strong time and weak times, ebbs and flows. Most of these fluctuations come from the outlook of the investors. And since the investors are human, they let outside factors affect their judgements. <br>
<br>
The confidence shatter caused by 9/11 has some pretty long ranging effects, especially on an economy that was at the time on a slower pace than it had been.<br>
<br>
Winning a war would probably reboost our confidence, though I would be impressed if we can ever actually have a victory in this war. <br>
<br>
When politics do affect the economy the lag effect is 2-3 years. So the slowdown that was happening at the time of 9/11 would have been a result of Clinton politics if it was politically caused at all.<br>
<br>
If Bush's politics do manage to turn the economy around, we will probably see the results during the next Clinton presidency.<br>
<br>
