</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#666666><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ughie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ghie</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 496<br> <font color=#E9D756>(7/16/02 8:12:08 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3470.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: where does this stuff come from?</span><hr size=1> I couldnt name a serious economist if you paid me.<br>
<br>
But I don't know what rock you were hiding under last(or any) election year when every bloody economist in the world was saying that you couldn't attribute the economy to Clinton policy..it was all part of a growth pattern started by Reagan...<br>
<br>
I don't believe any of it. <br>
<br>
Most economist agree that any election will boost the economy. At the same time they agree that outside of sweeping reforms (which are nearly impossible in todays political environment) politics don't have much effect on the economy and it is in fact the other way around.<br>
<br>
The Economy effects politics. More precisely: we blame politics for the economy and a bad economy will result in political changes.<br>
<br>
The biggest factor that the president can play on the economy is how he talks about it. If the president says we will have it rough, the economy will stumble. If the president says we can expect to see significant growth...the economy will get a push upward...<br>
<br>
Those effects are immediate.<br>
<br>
But the time it takes for policy to effect the economy is 2-3 years, mostly because from the time a policy is announced to the time it takes effect is about 1-2 years.<br>
<br>
Most economists study the economy to see how we will fare in the upcoming months. Those that study politics are trying to make more money and sell a book or something. Economics is boring, politics are still boring but sell more books.<br>
<br>
The single biggest factor in the economy is the outlook of investors. If they are happy and positive the economy will improve. <br>
<br>
The second biggest factor in the economy is innovation. If something new hits the market that everyone has to have, that drives the economy forward.<br>
<br>
Presidential statements have an effect on the first of those two factors, but in the big picture it is the economy that affects the economy most, not politics.<br>
 <p><CENTER>G
MF Virtuoso</CENTER>

